        <h3 style="margin-top: 60px;" >Genetic origin</h3>
        <p style="color:rgb(10, 10, 10);">
            Common wheat is a hexaploid plant resulting from two successive natural hybridizations that increased the chromosome number from 14 to 42.
            The first natural cross occurred between two wild diploid species, Triticum urartu, a wild form of Triticum monococcum (2n = 14, genome AA), and T. Sitopsis (2n = 14, genome BB), resulting in tetraploid wheat, Triticum dicoccoides (2n = 28, genome AABB). The hybridization of T. dicoccoides with a wild grass, T. tauschii, with the genome DD, gave rise to 
            the current common wheat, Triticum aestivum (F. Samoulian, 2009).
        </p>




