        <h3 style="margin-top: 60px;" >Genetic origin</h3>
        <p style="color:rgb(10, 10, 10);">
            Durum wheat (T. turgidum ssp. durum Desf.) is an allo-tetraploid species (2n = 28, AABB) that originated from hybridization followed by chromosomal doubling between Triticum urartu (genome AA) and a closely related species of Aegilops speltoides (genome BB) (Huang et al., 2002).

            Wheat traces its origin back to a wild form of the diploid species (Triticum monococcum) sensu lato in a region encompassing Iran, Syria, and Turkey. The first tetraploid species, Triticum turgidum, resulted from hybridization between Triticum monococcum and a wheat-related grass called Aegilops speltoides. The first species contributed the A genome, and the latter contributed the B genome. The domestication of this tetraploid wheat (AABB) gave rise to durum wheat, 
            which is the origin of cultivated durum wheat varieties (Feldman, 1976).
